Data Analysis of Week 3 Example Data

Priscilla Cuellar-Rocha

2023-07-26

Overview

This report presents primary data analysis for the Week 3 example data. Specifically, this will report basic descriptive statistics as well as report tests of the following predictions:

  1. People will feel more guilt when:
  • 1.1. They caused the shock (vs. their partner)
  • 1.2. The partner is morally good (vs. bad)
  • 1.3. The shock is stronger (high > medium > low)
  1. Women will report more guilt than men
  2. Agreeable people will report more guilt
  3. Neurotic people will report more guilt

and

  1. People will be more generous when:
  • 5.1 They caused the shock (vs. their partner)
  • 5.2 The partner is morally good (vs. bad)
  • 5.3 The shock is stronger (high > medium > low)
  1. Women will be more generous than men
  2. Agreeable people will be more generous
  3. Neurotic people will be more generous
#Load in the data
data<-read.csv("Week 3/Processed Data/Week 3 Data PROCESSED.csv")

#Recode variables:
data$PIN<-as.factor(data$PIN)
data$sex<-as.factor(data$sex)
data$shock<-as.factor(data$shock)
data$shockCause<-as.factor(data$shockCause)
data$pMoral<-as.factor(data$pMoral)

Guilt Analyses

Prediction 1.1

Prediction 1.1 was supported. People felt more guilty when they caused the shock:

#Run the t-test for prediction 1.1
p1.1<-t.test(data$guilt~data$shockCause)

#Output the result
p1.1
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  data$guilt by data$shockCause
## t = -11.016, df = 708.25, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group 0 and group 1 is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -1.1502070 -0.8022365
## sample estimates:
## mean in group 0 mean in group 1 
##        3.511173        4.487395
plot1.1 <- ggplot(data=data,aes(x=shockCause, y=guilt, fill = shockCause)) +
  labs(x= "Cause of Shock",
       y= "Guilt") +
  stat_summary(fun = "mean",
               geom = "bar",
               position = "dodge") +
  stat_summary(fun.data = "mean_cl_boot",
               geom = "errorbar",
               position = "dodge") +
  #this will bootstrap (estimate) what the errors should be
  scale_x_discrete(labels=c("Partner Inflict","Self Inflict")) +
  scale_fill_manual(values=c("purple2",  "pink"),
                    guide=F) +
  theme_grey(base_size=20)

Prediction 1.3

Prediction 1.3 was supported. People felt more guilty when the shock was stronger:

#Run the ANOVA for prediction 1.3
p1.3<-lm(guilt~shock,data=data)

#Output the result
anova(p1.3)
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Response: guilt
##            Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value    Pr(>F)

## Residuals 712 977.14   1.372                      
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
#Output the group means
tapply(data$guilt,data$shock,function(x) mean(x,na.rm=T))
##        0        1        2 
## 3.350211 4.012605 4.625000
#Generate the plot

plot1.3 <- ggplot(data=data,
                  aes(x=shock,
                      y=guilt,
                      fill=shock)) +
  labs(x = "Shock Values", y="Guilt") +
  scale_shape_discrete(labels=c("Low","Medium","High")) +
  theme_gray(base_size=20) +

Prediction 3

Prediction 3 was supported. Agreeable people reported more guilt:

#Run the correlation test for prediction 3
p3<-cor.test(data$agre,data$guilt)

#Output the result
p3
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  data$agre and data$guilt
## t = 4.3382, df = 713, p-value = 1.644e-05
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.08807907 0.23096956
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.1603644
#Plot a linear model

plot3 <- ggplot(data=data,
                aes(x=agre,
                    y=guilt)) +
  labs(x="Participant Agreebleness",
       y="Guilt") +
  theme_gray(base_size = 20) +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method=lm)

Prediction 4
